							I'd say confront her on what you see as the problem in as supportive a way as possible. I would also not let your kid around her until you feel the child won't be the target of the ire. Emotional abuse can lead to as many scars as physical abuse years down the line. I would point out she has been getting increasingly angry and lashing out at random. Offer support but explain you just aren't willing to subject yourself or your child to the irate rantings and attacks. I don't think it is likely to work, but it is the best option I could think of with the limited info. Just do your best not to attack and express some desire to help.
