					<a href="showthread.php?p=1769063#post1769063" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">I'd say confront her on what you see as the problem in as supportive a way as possible. I would also not let your kid around her until you feel the child won't be the target of the ire. Emotional abuse can lead to as many scars as physical abuse years down the line. I would point out she has been getting increasingly angry and lashing out at random. Offer support but explain you just aren't willing to subject yourself or your child to the irate rantings and attacks. I don't think it is likely to work, but it is the best option I could think of with the limited info. Just do your best not to attack and express some desire to help.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>The problem with confrontation on this is that I'm not really in a position where I can pipe up. I'd be interjecting. Exceeding my brief. No matter how I did it, it would be seen as me sticking my nose into a family affair that I didn't belong in because I'm not a blood relative.<br />
<br />
I've already started riding the &quot;don't let the kid anywhere near her right now&quot; train because I'm as familiar with emotional abuse as I am with physical. They leave different scars, but they're still scars. Thanks for that warning.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>MI Redeux</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1769050#post1769050" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Why do you think it is a mental illness?  The person may just be extremely stressed due to financial crisis or some other major life changing event.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>The fact that I just now found out that she's been like this her whole life, just keeping it under wraps for the sake of politeness in the face of people who are not blood relatives.<br />
<br />
The number of people who have come out of the woodwork after this and said that they're actually afraid of her but wouldn't dare to so much as comment on it due to the berating it would entail is frightening.<br />
<br />
My worst fear after how bad this could get for my wife and kid is that this will be the end to any honest non-posturing contact I can have with this person.<br />
<br />
I forgive very easily when wrong is done to me but it's part of my duty to protect my child from suffering wrongdoing if I am capable.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
